**Describe the bug**

Calling clone() on a TextGeometry results in a console error: `THREE.TextGeometry: font parameter is not an instance of THREE.Font.`
Since f2e342e98bf31026623e1dd6608d2c173654281d `this.contructor()` is called in clone(), and that's why TextGeometry is reporting the missing font

***Code***

```js
const loader = new THREE.FontLoader();
loader.load('helvetiker_regular.typeface.json',
    (loadedFont) => {
        const geometry = new THREE.TextGeometry('test', {
            font: loadedFont,
            size: 100,
            height: 1,
            curveSegments: 12,
        });
        geometry.clone();
    });
```

**Expected behavior**

The TextGeometry should be cloned without any console output

**Platform:**

 - Device: Desktop
 - OS: Linux
 - Browser: Chrome
 - Three.js version: r136

I found a check in the GLTFParser to exclude Safari and Firfox to use the TextureLoader instead of the ImageBitmapLoader in the code
```js
if ( typeof createImageBitmap !== 'undefined' && /Firefox|safari/.test( navigator.userAgent ) === false ) {

	this.textureLoader = new ImageBitmapLoader( this.options.manager );

} else {

	this.textureLoader = new TextureLoader( this.options.manager );

}
```

The regex unfortunately filters any chromium based browser because they include 'safari' in their userAgent.

I'd prefer to pass a Loading Manager for the parser but expanding the regex would be a quick fix.
```js
if ( typeof createImageBitmap !== 'undefined' && /Firefox|^((?!chrome|android).)*safari/i.test( navigator.userAgent ) === false ) {
...
```

**Describe the bug**

DDS and PNG textures lose all color, I don't know how to really explain, I attached screenshots bellow. Since I only use these 2 types of textures, I can't test other types.

If the browser has DDS support, it will be used, otherwise fallback to PNG. This happens on all browsers and devices I tested.

**To Reproduce**

Steps to reproduce the behavior:
Go to either of the live examples below and press on a weapon or amor icon, the differences will be visible.

***Code***

A code snippet of how I'm using it.
```ts
		const manager = new THREE.LoadingManager(() => {
			const loadingScreen = document.getElementById('loading-screen')
			if (loadingScreen) {
				loadingScreen.classList.add('fade-out')

				loadingScreen!.addEventListener('transitionend', onTransitionEnd)
			}
		})
		manager.addHandler(/\.dds$/i, new DDSLoader())

		const mtlLoader = new MTLLoader(manager)
		mtlLoader.setPath(url!)
		mtlLoader.load(`${model}.mtl`, (materials) => {
			materials.preload()

			const objLoader = new OBJLoader(manager)
			objLoader.setMaterials(materials)
			objLoader.setPath(url!)
			objLoader.load(`${model}.obj`, (object) => {
				object.scale.setScalar(1 / 200)

				object.traverse((child) => {
					child.frustumCulled = false
					if ((child as any).material instanceof THREE.MeshPhongMaterial) {
						(child as any).material.side = THREE.DoubleSide
					}
				})
				scene.add(object)
			}, undefined, (error) => console.error(error))
		})
```

