**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**

The WebGLRenderer should not be recomputing all the matrices of all the objects of the scene when `matrixWorldAutoUpdate` is set to true. Just the one that effectively changed.

```js
if ( scene.matrixWorldAutoUpdate === true ) scene.updateMatrixWorld();
```
Here we are basically browsing the full scene and updating parents and children even if nothing changed or if the scene only partially changed.

**Describe the solution you'd like**

For me, it would be nice to have a way to determine which objects of the scene are dirty and which ones are pristine.
That way, we would update the matrices of the subtree where the parent node is dirty. 

Due to the lack of encapsulation of the Object3D API, I don't see how we could achieve to have the state of the object set to dirty when the object is transformed (position, rotation, scale).
I think that any operation that would change the position, the rotation, the scale should be marking the object as dirty.

This dirty status would be helpful to fix the raycasting on #24736, because we would just have to search for dirty parents in the ancestors of the object against the raycasting is done.

```js
//Object3D
setPosition(newPosition: Vector3) {
    this.isDirty = true;
    //...
}
//...

searchForDirty() {
    if (this.isDirty) {
        this.updateMatrixWorld();
        return;
    }
    this.children.forEach(child => child.searchForDirty())
}


//WebGLRenderer
//...
// update scene graph
if (scene.matrixWorldAutoUpdate === true) scene.searchForDirty();
//...
```

** Alternative solutions **
Basically in this [link](https://threejs.org/docs/index.html#manual/en/introduction/Matrix-transformations) it is explained that we can obtain better performances by managing ourselves the update of matrices. 

**Additional context**

I thought that matrixWorldNeedsUpdate was the way to know if an Object3D is dirty, but it is always set to true by `updateMatrix()` if you have `matrixAutoUpdate` set to true. So basically, when the scene is calling updateMatrixWorld(), the whole graph's matrices are recomputed even if there is nothing or few subtree to update.

```js
        updateMatrixWorld( force ) {
		if ( this.matrixAutoUpdate ) this.updateMatrix();
               //...
        }

        updateMatrix() {
		this.matrix.compose( this.position, this.quaternion, this.scale );

		this.matrixWorldNeedsUpdate = true;

	}
```

**Note**: It implies a lot of thing, and we may need to work on a smarter approach than my proposition, but I think it is worth to work on it.

