**Describe the bug**

It is not possible to `flipY` a texture that has been loaded through the current `GLTFLoader` when it uses `ImageBitmapLoader`.

https://threejs.org/docs/#api/en/textures/Texture.flipY states:
`Note that this property has no effect for ImageBitmap. You need to configure on bitmap creation instead. See ImageBitmapLoader.`

The only arguments that can be passed to the GLTFLoader are the LoadingManager. 

When the `GLTFParser` is constructed, an `ImageBitmapLoader` is created, but there is no allowance in setting any options for it, eg `{ imageOrientation: 'flipY' }`.

https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/blob/master/examples/jsm/loaders/GLTFLoader.js#L2278
```js
if ( typeof createImageBitmap === 'undefined' || isSafari || ( isFirefox && firefoxVersion < 98 ) ) {
    this.textureLoader = new TextureLoader( this.options.manager );
    // this.textureLoader is not accessible to set options on,
    // eg, this.textureLoader.setOptions( { imageOrientation: 'flipY' } );
} else {
    this.textureLoader = new ImageBitmapLoader( this.options.manager );
}
```

**Fix**

I'm happy to add a fix by:
- Allowing the passing of an additional options object to the GLTFLoader directly `new GLTFLoader(loadingManager, { textureLoaderOptions: { imageOrientation: 'flipY' } } )`
- Adding an generic options attribute to GLTFLoader `parse` and `load` method that are passed into the `GLTFParser` constructor
- Adding a generic `setOptions` method to GLTFLoader, than will set options, which will be interrogated and retrieved when passing to the `GLTFParser` constructor
- A specific variation of any of the above
- Any other suggestions welcome

Apologies if anything is wrong with this statement.

