material.onBuild( object, parameters, _this );
material.onBeforeCompile( parameters, _this );
program = programCache.acquireProgram( parameters, programCacheKey );
```

Note, that `programCacheKey` is computed **before** `onBuild`, so `onBuild` and `onBeforeCompile` can't influence it. So if `programCacheKey` exists in cache, then any changes to `parameters` in `onBeforeCompile` and `onBuild` discarded as `parameters` variable is not used if the program received from the cache. 

Why: it's very confusing that `onBeforeCompile` runs, but the code does not impact the state at all. Had to dig into the source code to understand what is happening. I think the metric "number of lookups in three.js source code" should be minimized for developers to be happy. 

### Solution

There is a bit of a problem that those callbacks also take other arguments as parameters:

-  `onBuild` and `onBeforeCompile` also take `renderer` as parameter, but I did not find any example where this argument was used. `onBeforeCompile` is mainly used to change shader.
- `onBuild` also takes `object` so this function can change state if it does something to object.

I do not know what the solution should be, maybe the simplest one, that won't change the API much is to do something along these lines: 

```
function findProgram( cacheKey ) { 
    let program;
    
    // Check if code has been already compiled
    for ( let p = 0, pl = programs.length; p < pl; p ++ ) {
    
	    const preexistingProgram = programs[ p ];
    
	    if ( preexistingProgram.cacheKey === cacheKey ) {
    
		    program = preexistingProgram;
		    ++ program.usedTimes;
    
		    break;
    
	    }
    
    }
    return program;
}

program = findProgram(programCacheKey);

material.onBuild( object, parameters, _this, program === undefined );
material.onBeforeCompile( parameters, _this, program === undefined );

program = programCache.acquireProgram( parameters, programCacheKey );
```

Basically telling whether the changes in parameters will change anything or not. Though, on the second thought, this is not a good solution as people will be copy-pasting a existing code code from examples that looks like this 

```
material.onBeforeCompile = (shader) => { ... } 
```

and will have no idea about the third argument and will be confused as well with the same issue. 


### Alternatives

Ideally, the API probably needs a bit more granularity, `onBeforeCompile` should be called only when the compile happens. But I have no idea what the API should be as I do not understand well what are the use cases for these two callbacks other than editing shader code and uniforms. 

Maybe a way to go is to make `onBeforeCompile` run only for now-being-compiled shaders and introduce `onBeforeAcquiringProgram` with the same arguments that will be called either in other cases or every time. 

