### Description

Vertex shaders of materials using shadowmaps fail to compile if there is at least one SpotLight and one DirectionalLight or PointLight in the scene casting shadows, but the shadowmap is not enabled.

The critical part of the error message is `'directionalLightShadows' : undeclared identifier`.

This is probably due to the change introduced in https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/pull/24564 , where the following condition:
 https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/blob/f19f1406667bcdf41e09d8ccfc11ffc8af6d3f33/src/renderers/shaders/ShaderChunk/shadowmap_vertex.glsl.js#L2 
 
 ...included `|| ( NUM_SPOT_LIGHT_COORDS > 0 )`, while the definition:
 https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/blob/f19f1406667bcdf41e09d8ccfc11ffc8af6d3f33/src/renderers/shaders/ShaderChunk/shadowmap_pars_vertex.glsl.js#L24
 
 ... is conditioned on `#ifdef USE_SHADOWMAP` and `#if NUM_DIR_LIGHT_SHADOWS > 0` only. That is, the identifier `directionalLightShadows` only gets defined when there is a shadow map and some directional lights. However, it gets used regardless of shadow map if there are any spot lights. The same holds for point lights.


### Reproduction steps

1. Add a SpotLight and a Directional/PointLight to a scene.
2. Make them both cast shadows.
3. Add an object with MeshStandardMaterial which receives shadows.
4. Make sure the shadowMap on the renderer is not enabled.
5. Render the scene and observe the compilation error.


