### Description

I have an application that renders only on demand (mouse move, button  pressed ...) since it has an static scene an in this way it can have a lower battery consumption. For texture loading I use the call new TextureLoader().loadAsync, but I use it inside a traverse call, since there are children that must have a texture. The problem is that the callback of traverse is not awaited, making the async code delay the texture painting, and since I have a render on demand, there is no texture when I render the scene.

### Solution

The solution would be to make the traverse call async :

	async traverse( callback ) {

		await callback( this );

		const children = this.children;

		for ( let i = 0, l = children.length; i < l; i ++ ) {

			await children[ i ].traverse( callback );

		}

	}

Making it this way there is no broken code and callbacks are awaited.

### Alternatives

An alternative would be to make a new method called traverseAsync, but there are other traverse methods, such as traverseVisible and traverseAncestors that also could be async, so I guess it is cleaner to make them all async instead of creating 3 more methods.

